the syllabus over there.

00:00:56.270 --> 00:01:00.100
So the first thing that
you're going to focus on

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:03.620
is, what is it that
you're trying to describe?

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:06.960
And these are the
equilibrium properties

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:10.120
that are described
best through what

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:12.040
I've been doing
section one, which

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:14.960
has to do with thermodynamics.

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:17.430
You'll start today
with thermodynamics.

00:01:17.430 --> 00:01:20.700
Basically, it's a
phenomenological approach,

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:22.630
so you essentially
look at something,

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:25.070
as kind of a black
box, without knowing

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:27.160
what the ingredients
are, and try

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:32.560
to give some kind of
description of how it's

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:34.600
function and properties change.

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:37.710
And these can be captured, for
the case of thermal properties

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:40.760
of matter through the laws of
thermodynamics, which we will

00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:44.740
set out in this first section,
which will roughly take us

00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:48.560
the first four
lectures of the course.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:51.270
Then I said that
statistical mechanics

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:54.010
is a probabilistic approach.

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:59.700
So we need to establish what
the language of probability is.

00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:03.980
And that can be the
topic for the second two

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:06.130
and half lectures of the course.

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:11.280
It is something that is less
physics-y, but since the topic

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:14.286
itself has to deal
with probabilities,

00:02:14.286 --> 00:02:17.770
it is very important,
from my perspective,

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:23.510
to set out the language and
the properties of systems

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:25.890
that are described
probabilistically.

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:29.020
Separately, we'll devote a
couple of lectures to do so.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:32.060
And in particular,
it is very important

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:34.750
that the laws of
probability, kind of,

00:02:34.750 --> 00:02:39.860
simplify when you're
dealing with a large number

00:02:39.860 --> 00:02:44.560
of variables, as captured,
for example, by what we

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.850
call the central limit theorem.

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:50.000
So you can see that the
third element of this course,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.540
which is the law
of large numbers,

00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:57.230
is inherent also to what
simplification you will

00:02:57.230 --> 00:03:00.630
see in the section
on probability.

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:03.510
And feeds back
very much into how

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:07.410
statistical mechanics
is developed.

00:03:07.410 --> 00:03:11.180
But then we said large
number of degrees of freedom.

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:12.800
So what are these
degrees of freedom?

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:18.440
Well, this is now taking
a different perspective.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:20.480
For us in
thermodynamics, when you

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:24.130
look at the system
as a black box,

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:29.320
and try to develop laws
based on observations,

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:31.970
we say that well, from the
perspective of physics,

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:35.270
we know that this box
contains atoms and molecules.

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:37.240
And these atoms
and molecules are

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:42.690
following very specific laws,
either from Newtonian mechanics

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:44.250
or quantum mechanics.

00:03:44.250 --> 00:03:48.550
And so if we know everything
about how atoms and molecules

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:51.840
behave, then we should
be able to derive

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:54.290
how large collections
of them behave.

00:03:54.290 --> 00:03:58.110
And get the laws
of thermodynamics

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:01.750
as a consequence of these
microscopic degrees of freedom

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:03.540
and their dynamics.

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:07.020
And so that's what
we will discuss

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:08.640
in the third part
of the course that

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.080
is devoted to kinetic theory.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:14.660
We will see that even at that
stage, it is beneficial to,

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:19.399
rather than follow individual
particles in a system,

00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:21.670
to adopt a
probabilistic approach,

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:25.200
and think about densities,
and how those densities evolve

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.920
according to
Liouville's Theorem.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.450
And what we will try
to also establish

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:35.000
is a very distinct
difference that

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.970
exists between
thermodynamics, and where

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:38.830
things are
irreversible and going

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:42.730
one direction, and Newtonian,
or quantum mechanics,

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:45.160
where things are
reversible in time.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:49.150
And we'll see that really
it's a matter of adapting

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:53.100
the right perspective in
order to see that these two

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.270
ways of looking
at the same system

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:57.950
are not in contradiction.

00:04:57.950 --> 00:05:01.290
So having established
these elements,

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:07.070
we will then finally
be in the place

00:05:07.070 --> 00:05:11.700
where we can discuss
statistical mechanics in terms

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:17.680
of some postulates about
how probabilities behave

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:20.580
for systems that
are in equilibrium.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:22.490
And how based on
those postulates,

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:26.020
we can then derive all
the laws of thermodynamics

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:29.410
and all the properties of
thermodynamics systems.

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:31.920
That they're ordained
while observations

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:36.100
and phenomenological
theories before.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:38.785
Now initially, in
section four, we

00:05:38.785 --> 00:05:42.690
will do that in the context of
classical systems-- description

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:46.870
of particles following
classical laws of motion.

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:48.950
And, again, as a
first simplification,

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:52.930
we will typically deal with
non-interacting systems,

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:54.420
such as ideal gas.

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:57.060
And make sure that we
understand the properties

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.570
of this important
fundamental system

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:03.500
from all possible perspectives.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:08.860
Then in section five, we will
go on to more realistic systems

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:12.210
where there are interactions
among these particles.

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:15.040
And there are two ways to
then deal with interactions.

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:18.220
You can either go by the
way of perturbation theory.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:21.130
We can start with ideal
system and add a little bit

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:23.970
of interaction, and see
how that changes things.

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:28.300
And we develop some elements of
graphical perturbation theories

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:29.920
in this context.

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:31.840
Or, you can take
another perspective,

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:35.020
and say that because of the
presence of interactions,

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:38.270
the system really adopts
a totally different type

00:06:38.270 --> 00:06:39.410
of behavior.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:41.570
And there's a perspective
known as mean field

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:43.940
theory that allows
you to do that.

00:06:43.940 --> 00:06:46.510
Then see how the
same system can be

00:06:46.510 --> 00:06:48.740
present in different
phases of matter,

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:52.830
such as liquids and gas,
and how this mean field

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:56.110
type of prescription
allows you to discuss

00:06:56.110 --> 00:07:00.360
the transitions between the
different types of behavior.

00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:04.920
Eventually, you will go on,
towards the last quarter

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:09.430
of the course, rather than the
classical description of matter

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:12.890
to a quantum description of the
microscopic degrees of freedom.

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:17.090
And we will see how the
differences and similarities

00:07:17.090 --> 00:07:19.210
between quantum
statistical mechanics,

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:21.870
classical statistical
mechanics, emerge.

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:23.860
And just, historically,
of course,

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:27.660
radius macroscopic properties
of the matter, the black body

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:30.100
laws, or heat
capacities, have been

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.120
very important in
showing the limitations

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.860
of classical description
of matter, and the need

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:40.730
to have something else, such
as the quantum description.

00:07:40.730 --> 00:07:44.070
We will not spend too much
time, more than three lectures,

00:07:44.070 --> 00:07:48.380
