00:32:50.540 --> 00:33:02.210
if two systems-- let's call
them A and B-- are separately

00:33:02.210 --> 00:33:18.940
in equilibrium with C--
with a third system-- then

00:33:18.940 --> 00:33:20.620
they are in equilibrium
with each other.

00:33:34.710 --> 00:33:37.700
This is sort of this
statement that the property

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:41.765
of equilibrium has the
character of transitivity.

00:33:50.440 --> 00:33:59.310
So what that means, pictorially,
is something like this.

00:34:02.670 --> 00:34:15.040
Suppose I have my two boxes,
A and B. And the third system

00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:19.960
that we're calling C.
And we've established

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:23.690
that A and B are separately
in thermal equilibrium with C,

00:34:23.690 --> 00:34:28.949
which means that we have
allowed exchange of heat

00:34:28.949 --> 00:34:33.610
to take place between A
and C, between B and C,

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:36.564
but currently, we
assume nothing--

00:34:36.564 --> 00:34:42.050
or we assume that B and C are
not connected to each other.

00:34:42.050 --> 00:34:44.210
The statement of
the law is that if I

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:57.650
were to replace this red with
green, so that I have also

00:34:57.650 --> 00:35:02.700
exchange that is going
on between A and B,

00:35:02.700 --> 00:35:04.870
then nothing happens.

00:35:04.870 --> 00:35:07.450
A and B are already
in equilibrium,

00:35:07.450 --> 00:35:11.960
and the fact that you open
the possibility of exchange

00:35:11.960 --> 00:35:15.730
of heat between them
does not change things.

00:35:15.730 --> 00:35:20.060
And again, this is this
consequence of transitivity.

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:24.030
And one of its kind of
important implications

00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:27.230
ultimately is that
we are allowed now

00:35:27.230 --> 00:35:32.480
based on this to add one more
coordinate to this description

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:34.810
that you have.

00:35:34.810 --> 00:35:38.730
That coordinate is the
analog of temperature.

00:35:38.730 --> 00:35:47.460
So this transitivity really
implies the existence

00:35:47.460 --> 00:35:49.620
of some kind of
empirical temperature.

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:57.160
And you may say well, this
is such an obvious thing,

00:35:57.160 --> 00:35:59.140
there should be transitivity.

00:35:59.140 --> 00:36:01.580
Well, I want to
usually give people

00:36:01.580 --> 00:36:05.960
examples that transitivity
is not a universal property,

00:36:05.960 --> 00:36:06.960
by as follows.

00:36:06.960 --> 00:36:10.390
Suppose that within
this room, there

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:13.240
is A who wants to
go on a date with C,

00:36:13.240 --> 00:36:15.930
and B who wants to
go on a date with C.

00:36:15.930 --> 00:36:19.190
I'm pretty sure that it's not
going to be the property that A

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:25.530
wants to go through the
date with B. It's 20%.

00:36:25.530 --> 00:36:26.040
All right.

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:34.080
So let's see how
we can ensure this.

00:36:34.080 --> 00:36:40.400
So we said that if some system
has reached equilibrium,

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:42.440
it has some set of coordinates.

00:36:42.440 --> 00:36:44.260
Let's call them
A1, A2, et cetera.

00:36:44.260 --> 00:36:45.430
There's some number of them.

00:36:45.430 --> 00:36:46.660
We don't know.

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:50.040
Similarly, here, we
have C1, C2, et cetera.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:55.130
And for B, we have B1, B2.

00:36:55.130 --> 00:37:03.200
Now what does it mean that I
have equilibrium of A and B?

00:37:03.200 --> 00:37:09.010
The implication is that if
I have a system by itself,

00:37:09.010 --> 00:37:11.130
I have a bunch of
possible coordinates.

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:13.610
I can be anywhere in
this coordinate space.

00:37:13.610 --> 00:37:16.440
And if I separately
have system C,

00:37:16.440 --> 00:37:18.420
I have another bunch
of coordinates.

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:21.700
And I can be anywhere in
this coordinate space.

00:37:21.700 --> 00:37:26.150
But if I force A and B to come
together and exchange heat

00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:29.420
and reaches equilibrium,
that is a constraint,

00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:32.820
which means that this set of
coordinates of the two cannot

00:37:32.820 --> 00:37:34.660
be independently varied.

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:38.980
There has to be some functional
relationship between them,

00:37:38.980 --> 00:37:43.750
which we can, for example,
cast into this form.

00:37:43.750 --> 00:37:46.270
So equilibrium, one
constraint, one kind

00:37:46.270 --> 00:37:48.310
of mathematical relation.

00:37:48.310 --> 00:37:51.470
Similarly, equilibrium
of-- this was A

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:57.510
and C, B and C-- would
give us some other function

00:37:57.510 --> 00:38:07.080
BC of coordinates of B and
coordinates of C equal to 0.

00:38:07.080 --> 00:38:09.730
OK?

00:38:09.730 --> 00:38:15.540
So there is one
thing that I can do.

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:21.960
I can take this expression
and recast it, and write it

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:25.160
as let's say, the first
coordinate that describes

00:38:25.160 --> 00:38:29.500
C is some other function,
which I will call big F

00:38:29.500 --> 00:38:36.600
AC of coordinates of
A. And all coordinates

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:41.650
of C, except the first
one that I have removed.

00:38:41.650 --> 00:38:44.130
Yes?

00:38:44.130 --> 00:38:47.810
AUDIENCE: When you
put that function F

00:38:47.810 --> 00:38:50.500
AC or all the coordinates of
A, and all the coordinates of C

00:38:50.500 --> 00:38:56.480
being zero, is that
[? polynomy ?] always going

00:38:56.480 --> 00:39:00.170
to be true for the first law,
or do you just give an example?

00:39:07.340 --> 00:39:10.130
PROFESSOR: It will
be always true

00:39:10.130 --> 00:39:14.360
that I have some set
of coordinates for 1,

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:18.200
some set of coordinates
with 2, and equilibrium

00:39:18.200 --> 00:39:20.460
for the two sets
of coordinates is

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:24.010
going to be expressible in
terms of some function that

00:39:24.010 --> 00:39:26.230
could be arbitrarily
complicated.

00:39:26.230 --> 00:39:29.240
It may be that I
can't even write this,

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:33.220
but I have to graph it,
or some kind of place

00:39:33.220 --> 00:39:34.410
in the coordinates space.

00:39:34.410 --> 00:39:36.250
So what I mean is
the following, you

00:39:36.250 --> 00:39:38.560
can imagine some
higher dimensional

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:41.440
space that is spanned
by As and the Cs.

00:39:41.440 --> 00:39:44.160
And each point, where the
things are in equilibrium,

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:49.150
will be some-- you can put a
cross in this coordinate space.

00:39:49.150 --> 00:39:52.000
And you can span
the various places

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:53.910
where equilibration takes place.

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:57.490
And you will have a
surface in this space.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:00.280
And that surface potential you
can describe mathematically

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:02.354
like this.

00:40:02.354 --> 00:40:03.260
OK?

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:06.300
And similarly, I can
do the same thing.

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:09.540
And pick out coordinate
C1 here, and write it

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:22.020
as F BC of A1, A2, and C2,
C3-- sorry, this is B1, B2.

00:40:22.020 --> 00:40:26.020
Actually, this brings me, this
question, to maybe one point

00:40:26.020 --> 00:40:27.190
that I should make.

00:40:27.190 --> 00:40:31.270
That sometimes during this
course, I will do things,

00:40:31.270 --> 00:40:33.130
and maybe I will
even say that I do

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:36.330
things that are physically
rigorous, but maybe not

00:40:36.330 --> 00:40:38.460
so mathematically.

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:42.240
And one example of this is
precisely this statement.

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:44.010
That is, if you
give a mathematician

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:45.610
and there is a
function like this.

00:40:45.610 --> 00:40:48.329
And then you pick one,
C1, and you write it

00:40:48.329 --> 00:40:49.870
as a function of
all the others, they

00:40:49.870 --> 00:40:53.230
say, oh, how do know that
that's even possible, that this

00:40:53.230 --> 00:40:55.010
exists?

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:57.030
And generally, it isn't.

00:40:57.030 --> 00:40:59.860
A simple example would
be A squared plus C

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:04.590
squared equals to zero,
then C's multiple valued.

00:41:04.590 --> 00:41:08.390
So the reason this
is physically correct

00:41:08.390 --> 00:41:11.940
is because if we set up
this situation, and really

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:13.790
these very physical
quantities, I

00:41:13.790 --> 00:41:17.540
know that I dialed my
C1 to this number here,

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:19.560
and all of the other
things adjusted.

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:22.160
So this is kind
of physically OK,

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:25.420
although mathematically, you
would have to potentially do

00:41:25.420 --> 00:41:30.490
a lot of [INAUDIBLE] to
arrive at this stage.

00:41:30.490 --> 00:41:31.870
OK.

00:41:31.870 --> 00:41:36.870
So now if I have to put all
of those things together,

00:41:36.870 --> 00:41:40.540
the fact that I have
equilibrium of A and B,

00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:46.460
plus equilibrium
of B and C, then

00:41:46.460 --> 00:41:50.170
implies that there
is eliminating

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:52.890
C1 between these
two, some function

00:41:52.890 --> 00:41:57.120
that depends on the coordinates
of A and coordinates of C,

00:41:57.120 --> 00:42:00.870
starting from the second one,
equal to some other function.

00:42:00.870 --> 00:42:04.090
And these functions
could be very different,

00:42:04.090 --> 00:42:07.420
coordinates of B
and coordinates of C

00:42:07.420 --> 00:42:09.820
starting from the second one.

00:42:09.820 --> 00:42:10.350
Yes?

00:42:10.350 --> 00:42:12.562
AUDIENCE: Do you need A
and C on the left there?

00:42:12.562 --> 00:42:14.353
PROFESSOR: A and C,
and B and C. Thank you.

00:42:19.183 --> 00:42:20.640
OK?

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:24.410
So this, everything that
we have worked out here,

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:27.350
really concerns
putting the first part

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:32.870
of this equation in
mathematical form.

00:42:32.870 --> 00:42:35.730
But this statement--
in mathematical form--

00:42:35.730 --> 00:42:38.830
but given the first part
of this statement, that

00:42:38.830 --> 00:42:41.900
is, the second part
of the statement, that

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:47.710
is that I know that if I remove
that red and make it green,

00:42:47.710 --> 00:42:51.330
so that heat can exchange, for
the same values of A and B,

00:42:51.330 --> 00:42:54.880
A and B are in equilibrium, so I
know that there is a functional

00:42:54.880 --> 00:42:56.200
form.

00:42:56.200 --> 00:43:03.150
So this is equilibrium
of A and B, implies

00:43:03.150 --> 00:43:07.910
that there is this function
that we were looking at before,

00:43:07.910 --> 00:43:13.400
that relates
coordinates of A and B

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:15.430
that constrains the
equilibrium that

00:43:15.430 --> 00:43:19.880
should exist
between A and B. OK.

00:43:19.880 --> 00:43:23.650
So the first part of the
statement of the zeroth law,

00:43:23.650 --> 00:43:27.210
and the second part of the
statement of the zeroth law

00:43:27.210 --> 00:43:31.910
can be written mathematically
in these two forms.

00:43:31.910 --> 00:43:37.920
And the nice part
about the first part

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:41.300
is that it says that the
equilibrium constraint that I

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:44.930
have between A's and
B's can mathematically

00:43:44.930 --> 00:43:49.730
be kind of spread out into some
function on the left that only

00:43:49.730 --> 00:43:52.180
depends on the
coordinates of A, and some

00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:59.300
function on the right that only
depends on coordinates of B.

00:43:59.300 --> 00:44:02.210
So that's important,
because it says

00:44:02.210 --> 00:44:07.760
that ultimately the
equilibration between two

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:11.680
objects can be
cast mathematically

00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:13.760
as having some kind
of a function--

00:44:13.760 --> 00:44:16.700
and we don't know anything about
the form of that function--

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:20.540
that only depends on
the coordinates of A.

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:25.420
And equilibration
implies that there exists

00:44:25.420 --> 00:44:28.260
some other function
that only depends

00:44:28.260 --> 00:44:30.420
on the coordinates
of the other one.

00:44:30.420 --> 00:44:35.130
And in equilibrium, those
two functional forms

00:44:35.130 --> 00:44:37.330
have to be the same.

00:44:37.330 --> 00:44:44.010
Now, there's two ways of getting
to this statement from the two

00:44:44.010 --> 00:44:46.850
things that I have
within up there.

00:44:46.850 --> 00:44:50.610
One of them is to choose some
particular reference system

00:44:50.610 --> 00:44:54.450
for C. Let's say
your C is seawater

00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:57.490
at some particular
set of conditions.

00:44:57.490 --> 00:45:01.190
And so then, these
are really constants

00:45:01.190 --> 00:45:03.795
that are appropriate
to see water.

00:45:03.795 --> 00:45:06.710
And then you have
chosen a function that

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:10.340
depends on variables of A, of
course of some function of B.

00:45:10.340 --> 00:45:12.550
Or you can say,
well, I can replace

00:45:12.550 --> 00:45:14.710
this seawater by something else.

00:45:14.710 --> 00:45:18.220
And irrespective
of what I choose,

00:45:18.220 --> 00:45:22.500
A and B, there by our definition
in equilibrium with each other,

00:45:22.500 --> 00:45:27.650
no matter what I did with C. Or
some various range of C things

00:45:27.650 --> 00:45:31.670
that I can do, maintaining this
equilibrium between A and B.

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:34.350
So in that perspective,
the C variables

00:45:34.350 --> 00:45:35.870
are dummy coordinates.

00:45:35.870 --> 00:45:38.560
So you should be able
to cancel them out

00:45:38.560 --> 00:45:40.800
from the two sides
of the equation,

00:45:40.800 --> 00:45:44.910
and get some kind
of a form like this.

00:45:44.910 --> 00:45:47.980
Either way, what
that really means

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:55.740
is that if I list all of
the coordinates of, say, A,

00:45:55.740 --> 00:46:01.930
and I put it, say, in
equilibrium with a bath that

00:46:01.930 --> 00:46:04.650
is at some particular
temperature,

00:46:04.650 --> 00:46:07.580
the coordinates of A
and B are constrained

00:46:07.580 --> 00:46:11.020
to lie in some particular
surface that would correspond

00:46:11.020 --> 00:46:13.680
to that particular theta.

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:19.670
And if I have
another system for B,

00:46:19.670 --> 00:46:23.270
the isotherm could have
completely different for that

00:46:23.270 --> 00:46:24.750
data.

00:46:24.750 --> 00:46:27.800
But any time A and B
are in equilibrium,

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:30.555
they would be lying
on the isotherm that

00:46:30.555 --> 00:46:33.350
would correspond
to the same fate.

00:46:33.350 --> 00:46:36.580
Now, again, a mechanical
version of this,

00:46:36.580 --> 00:46:40.210
that is certainly
hopefully demystifies

00:46:40.210 --> 00:46:43.890
any mystification that may
remain, is to think a scale.

00:46:47.890 --> 00:46:50.050
You have something
A on this scale.

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:51.830
And you have something
C on this scale.

00:46:51.830 --> 00:46:53.355
And the scale is balanced.

00:46:53.355 --> 00:46:59.390
You replace A with B, and
B and C are in balance,

00:46:59.390 --> 00:47:02.220
then you know that A and B are
in balance with each other.

00:47:02.220 --> 00:47:04.450
And that implies
that, indeed, there

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:08.552
is a property of the objects
that you put on the balance.

00:47:08.552 --> 00:47:10.010
You can either
think of it as mass,

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:12.980
or more appropriately,
the gravitational force

00:47:12.980 --> 00:47:16.190
that they experience,
that they need.

00:47:16.190 --> 00:47:17.290
The thing is balanced.

00:47:17.290 --> 00:47:19.090
The forces are equal.

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:21.230
So it's essentially
the same thing.

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:23.520
Now having established
this, then you

00:47:23.520 --> 00:47:27.150
want to go and figure
out what the formula is

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:31.320
that relates the property
that needs to be balanced,

00:47:31.320 --> 00:47:34.120
which is maybe the mass or the
gravitational force in terms

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:36.530
of density, volume, et cetera.

00:47:36.530 --> 00:47:38.400
So that's what you
would like to do here.

00:47:38.400 --> 00:47:43.520
We would like to be able
to relate this temperature

00:47:43.520 --> 00:47:46.510
function to all the other
coordinates of the system,

00:47:46.510 --> 00:47:48.087
as we're going to.

00:47:48.087 --> 00:47:48.670
Any questions?

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:54.858
Yes?

00:47:54.858 --> 00:47:58.211
AUDIENCE: So how did [INAUDIBLE]
that there is the isotherm?

00:47:58.211 --> 00:48:01.570
Is it coming from the
second conclusion?

00:48:01.570 --> 00:48:02.310
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:48:02.310 --> 00:48:08.320
So what we have said is
that when two objects are

00:48:08.320 --> 00:48:13.170
in equilibrium, this
function is the same between.

00:48:13.170 --> 00:48:17.270
So let's say that we
pick some kind of a vat--

00:48:17.270 --> 00:48:19.190
like, it could be a lake.

00:48:19.190 --> 00:48:21.930
And we know that
the lake is so big

00:48:21.930 --> 00:48:24.710
that if you put something
in equilibrium with that,

00:48:24.710 --> 00:48:28.520
it's not extracting too much
heat or whatever from the lake

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:33.390
can change its
temperature function.

00:48:33.390 --> 00:48:37.300
So we put our system
in equilibrium

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:40.420
with the lake, which is
at some particular fixed

00:48:40.420 --> 00:48:41.130
value of theta.

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:45.520
And we don't know what theta
is, but it's a constant.

00:48:45.520 --> 00:48:48.560
So if I were to fiddle
around with the system

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:51.080
that I put in the lake--
I change its volume,

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:53.600
I change its length,
I do something--

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:55.850
and it stays in equilibrium
with the length,

00:48:55.850 --> 00:48:58.210
there is some function
of the coordinates

00:48:58.210 --> 00:49:01.160
of that system that
is equal to theta.

00:49:01.160 --> 00:49:07.320
So again, in general,
I can make a diagram

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:12.790
that has various coordinates
of the system, A1, A2, A3.

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:18.460
And for every combination
that is that this theta,

00:49:18.460 --> 00:49:20.700
I will put a point here.

00:49:20.700 --> 00:49:24.410
And in principle, I can
vary these coordinates.

00:49:24.410 --> 00:49:27.120
And this amounts
to one constraint

00:49:27.120 --> 00:49:30.160
in however many
dimensional space I have.

00:49:30.160 --> 00:49:34.170
So if we span some
kind of a surface--

00:49:34.170 --> 00:49:35.925
so if you're in three
dimension, there

00:49:35.925 --> 00:49:37.605
would be a two
dimensional surface.

00:49:37.605 --> 00:49:38.980
If you're in two
dimension, there

00:49:38.980 --> 00:49:42.950
would be a line that would
correspond to this constraint.

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:45.480
Presumably, if I change
the lake with something

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:47.860
else, so that theta
changes, I will

00:49:47.860 --> 00:49:51.685
be prescribing some other curve
and some other surface in this.

00:49:51.685 --> 00:49:58.415
Now these are surfaces
in coordinate space of A.

00:49:58.415 --> 00:50:02.880
In order to be in equilibrium
with an entity at the fixed

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:07.320
value of theta, they prescribe
some particular surface

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:10.765
in the entire coordinate space
and they're called isotherms.

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:18.560
OK?

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:20.740
Actually, let's
state that a little

00:50:20.740 --> 00:50:26.840
bit further, because
you would like

00:50:26.840 --> 00:50:31.020
to give a number to
temperature, so many degrees

00:50:31.020 --> 00:50:33.820
Celsius, or Fahrenheit,
or whatever.

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:36.700
So how do you do that?

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:45.670
And one way to do that is to
use what is called the ideal gas

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:49.330
temperature space--
the ideal gas scale.

00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:58.040
So you need some
property at this stage

00:50:58.040 --> 00:51:02.870
in order to construct
a temperature scale.

00:51:02.870 --> 00:51:07.810
And it turns out that a
gas is a system that we

00:51:07.810 --> 00:51:11.550
keep coming back
to again and again.

00:51:11.550 --> 00:51:15.670
So as I go through the various
laws of thermodynamics,

00:51:15.670 --> 00:51:18.260
I will mention
something special that

00:51:18.260 --> 00:51:23.100
happens to this law for
the case of this ideal gas.

00:51:23.100 --> 00:51:25.160
And actually, right
now, define also

00:51:25.160 --> 00:51:27.940
what I mean by the ideal gas.

00:51:27.940 --> 00:51:31.740
So we said that a
gas, in general, you

00:51:31.740 --> 00:51:37.710
can define through
coordinates P and V.

00:51:37.710 --> 00:51:42.140
So if I put this
gas in a piston,

00:51:42.140 --> 00:51:47.990
and I submerge this piston,
let's say in a lake,

00:51:47.990 --> 00:51:53.270
so that it is always at whatever
temperature this lake is.

00:51:53.270 --> 00:51:57.500
Then I can change
the volume of this,

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:00.080
and measure what the pressure
is, or change the pressure,

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:02.180
and figure out
what the volume is.

00:52:02.180 --> 00:52:08.180
And I find out that there is
a surface in this space where

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:11.850
this curve that corresponds
to being equilibrium

00:52:11.850 --> 00:52:15.780
with this [? leaves-- ?] this
is the measure of the isotherm.

00:52:15.780 --> 00:52:21.850
Now the ideal gas law is that
when I go to the limit there,

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:27.430
V goes to infinity,
or P goes to zero.

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:31.130
So that the whole thing
becomes very dilute.

00:52:31.130 --> 00:52:33.290
No matter what
gas you put here--

00:52:33.290 --> 00:52:35.400
whether it's argon,
oxygen, krypton,

00:52:35.400 --> 00:52:43.020
whatever-- you find that in this
limit, this shape of this curve

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:47.220
is special in the sense
that if you were to increase

00:52:47.220 --> 00:52:49.310
the volume by a factor
of two, the pressure

00:52:49.310 --> 00:52:51.670
will go down by a
factor of two, such

00:52:51.670 --> 00:52:53.740
that the product
PV is a constant.

00:52:58.160 --> 00:53:01.650
And again, this is
only true in the limit

00:53:01.650 --> 00:53:04.980
where either V goes to
infinity or P goes to 0.

00:53:04.980 --> 00:53:07.770
And this is the property
that all gases have.

00:53:10.480 --> 00:53:13.390
So you say OK, I will use that.

00:53:13.390 --> 00:53:17.000
Maybe I will define what
the value of this product

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:20.260
is to be the temperature.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:24.290
So if I were to replace
this bath with a bath that

00:53:24.290 --> 00:53:28.430
was hotter than this product
for the same amount of gas,

00:53:28.430 --> 00:53:30.590
for the same wire,
would be different.

00:53:30.590 --> 00:53:33.726
And I would get a
different constant.

00:53:33.726 --> 00:53:35.520
You maybe still want a number.

00:53:35.520 --> 00:53:40.400
So what you say is
that the temperature

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:51.340
of the system in degrees
Kelvin is 273 times 16.

00:53:51.340 --> 00:54:04.030
The limit of PV, as V goes
to infinity of your system,

00:54:04.030 --> 00:54:10.300
divided by the limit
of the same thing

00:54:10.300 --> 00:54:18.240
at the triple point
of water [? iced. ?]

00:54:22.070 --> 00:54:24.620
So what does that mean?

00:54:24.620 --> 00:54:29.090
So you have this
thing by which you

00:54:29.090 --> 00:54:31.330
want to measure temperature.

00:54:31.330 --> 00:54:33.860
You put it in contact
with the system-- could

00:54:33.860 --> 00:54:37.510
be a bath of water,
could be anything, yes?

00:54:37.510 --> 00:54:39.310
You go through this
exercise and you

00:54:39.310 --> 00:54:42.510
calculate what this product is.

00:54:42.510 --> 00:54:44.830
So you have this product.

00:54:44.830 --> 00:54:48.870
Then what you do is
you take your system,

00:54:48.870 --> 00:54:52.800
and you put it in a case
that there are icebergs,

00:54:52.800 --> 00:54:54.320
and there's water,
and there will

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:58.610
be some steam that will
naturally evaporate.

00:54:58.610 --> 00:55:02.080
So you calculate the
same product of PV

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:05.380
in this system that
is the triple point

00:55:05.380 --> 00:55:07.720
of ice water, et cetera.

00:55:07.720 --> 00:55:11.810
So you've measured one product
appropriate to your system,

00:55:11.810 --> 00:55:14.380
one product appropriate
to this reference

00:55:14.380 --> 00:55:19.290
point that people have set, and
then the ratio of those things

00:55:19.290 --> 00:55:22.340
is going to give you the
temperature of the system

00:55:22.340 --> 00:55:24.130
that you want to measure.

00:55:24.130 --> 00:55:27.740
This is clearly a very
convoluted way of doing things,

00:55:27.740 --> 00:55:31.150
but it's a kind of
rigorous definition of what

00:55:31.150 --> 00:55:34.470
the ideal gas
temperature scale is.

00:55:34.470 --> 00:55:38.300
And it depends on this
particular property

00:55:38.300 --> 00:55:44.290
of the diluted gases that the
production of PV is a constant.

00:55:44.290 --> 00:55:49.880
And again, this number
is set by definition

00:55:49.880 --> 00:55:53.930
to be the temperature of the
triple point of the ice water

00:55:53.930 --> 00:55:54.430
gas.

00:56:08.670 --> 00:56:10.634
OK.

00:56:10.634 --> 00:56:11.300
Other questions?

00:56:13.930 --> 00:56:14.820
All right.

00:56:14.820 --> 00:56:20.360
So this is now time to
go through the first law.

00:56:24.070 --> 00:56:28.470
Now I'll write again
this statement,

00:56:28.470 --> 00:56:31.690
and then we'll start to
discuss what it really means.

00:56:31.690 --> 00:56:56.250
So if the state of an otherwise
adiabatically isolated system

00:56:56.250 --> 00:57:14.750
is changed by work,
the amount of work

00:57:14.750 --> 00:57:22.900
is only function of
initial and final points.

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:32.740
OK.

00:57:32.740 --> 00:57:36.270
So let's parse what
that means and think

00:57:36.270 --> 00:57:38.000
about some particular example.

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:42.575
So let's imagine that we
have isolated some system.

00:57:46.570 --> 00:57:49.740
So that it's not
completely boring,

00:57:49.740 --> 00:57:52.380
let's imagine that
maybe it's a gas.

00:57:52.380 --> 00:57:56.590
So it has P and V as
some set of coordinates.

00:57:56.590 --> 00:58:00.470
Let's say that we put some
kind of a spring or wire in it,

00:58:00.470 --> 00:58:01.730
so we can pull on it.

00:58:01.730 --> 00:58:04.030
And we can ask how
much we pulled,

00:58:04.030 --> 00:58:07.410
and what is the
length of this system.

00:58:07.410 --> 00:58:09.530
Maybe we even put
a magnet in it,

00:58:09.530 --> 00:58:15.080
so we have magnetization
that we can measure

00:58:15.080 --> 00:58:19.070
if we were to pass
some kind of a current

00:58:19.070 --> 00:58:21.630
and exert some kind
of magnetic field.

00:58:21.630 --> 00:58:24.520
So there's a whole
bunch of coordinates

00:58:24.520 --> 00:58:30.420
that I'm completely familiar
with from doing my mechanics

00:58:30.420 --> 00:58:32.760
courses and
electromagnetic courses.

00:58:32.760 --> 00:58:38.880
So I know various ways to do
mechanical work on this system.

00:58:38.880 --> 00:58:43.630
So the system is
otherwise isolated,

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:48.640
because I don't really know how
to handle this concept of heat

00:58:48.640 --> 00:58:52.380
yet, but I certainly have no
problems with mechanical work.

00:58:52.380 --> 00:58:57.320
And so what I do is, I imagine
that it is initially isolated.

00:58:57.320 --> 00:59:01.570
What I do is therefore, I
have some-- in this case,

00:59:01.570 --> 00:59:03.780
six dimensional
coordinate space.

00:59:03.780 --> 00:59:06.940
I'm will only draw
two out of the six.

00:59:06.940 --> 00:59:12.640
And I start some initial
point, let's call it I.

00:59:12.640 --> 00:59:16.380
And then I start doing various
types of things to this.

00:59:16.380 --> 00:59:19.270
I could, for example,
first pull on this,

00:59:19.270 --> 00:59:21.110
so that the length
changes, changes

00:59:21.110 --> 00:59:24.810
the current, put
pressure so that

00:59:24.810 --> 00:59:26.840
the volume changes, et cetera.

00:59:26.840 --> 00:59:29.385
At the end of this story,
I'm at some other point

00:59:29.385 --> 00:59:32.250
that I will call F.

00:59:32.250 --> 00:59:36.980
Now I could have performed
this change from the initial

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:41.610
to the final state
through one set of changes

00:59:41.610 --> 00:59:44.640
taking place one
after the other.

00:59:44.640 --> 00:59:48.350
But maybe I will change that,
and I will perform things

00:59:48.350 --> 00:59:50.880
in a different way.

00:59:50.880 --> 00:59:52.380
So there's path number 1.

00:59:52.380 --> 00:59:53.820
Then there's path number 2.

00:59:53.820 --> 00:59:56.260
And there's huge number
of different paths

00:59:56.260 --> 00:59:59.990
that I can, in
principle, take in order

00:59:59.990 --> 01:00:04.720
to change between the
initial and final points

01:00:04.720 --> 01:00:08.540
by playing around with the
mechanical coordinates that

01:00:08.540 --> 01:00:10.190
describe the system.

01:00:10.190 --> 01:00:14.290
I always ensure that,
initially, I was in equilibrium,

01:00:14.290 --> 01:00:18.230
so I could know exactly what the
value of these parameters are.

01:00:18.230 --> 01:00:21.830
And finally, I wait until
I have reached equilibrium.

01:00:21.830 --> 01:00:25.050
So again, I know
what this things are.

01:00:25.050 --> 01:00:29.000
And I know what
mechanical work is.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.250
And I can calculate
along each one

01:00:31.250 --> 01:00:35.520
of these paths, the
net amount of work.

01:00:35.520 --> 01:00:37.392
The work is delivered
in different ways--

01:00:37.392 --> 01:00:39.350
through the magnetic
field, through the pulling

01:00:39.350 --> 01:00:41.530
of the spring, to the
hydrostatic pressure,

01:00:41.530 --> 01:00:44.180
et cetera-- but
ultimately, when I add up

01:00:44.180 --> 01:00:46.450
all of the increments
of the work,

01:00:46.450 --> 01:00:51.150
I will find that all of them
will give you the same delta

01:00:51.150 --> 01:00:56.180
W, irrespective of the path.

01:00:56.180 --> 01:00:57.410
OK.

01:00:57.410 --> 01:00:59.140
Now this reminds me
of the following,

01:00:59.140 --> 01:01:07.310
that if I'm rolling a
ball on top of a hill.

01:01:07.310 --> 01:01:09.410
And there is no friction.

01:01:09.410 --> 01:01:11.550
The amount of work
that I do in order

01:01:11.550 --> 01:01:15.450
to take it from here to here,
irrespective of the path

01:01:15.450 --> 01:01:17.540
that I take on the
hill, it really

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:20.380
is a function of the
difference in potential energy

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:23.240
between the final
and initial points.

01:01:23.240 --> 01:01:26.610
So it's the same type of thing.

01:01:26.610 --> 01:01:31.520
Rather than moving these
coordinates on a hill,

01:01:31.520 --> 01:01:35.740
I am moving them in
this set of parameters

01:01:35.740 --> 01:01:38.100
that thermodynamically
describe the system,

01:01:38.100 --> 01:01:40.120
but I see the same
thing that I would

01:01:40.120 --> 01:01:45.080
see in the absence of friction
for rolling a ball of the hill.

01:01:45.080 --> 01:01:47.290
And immediately, I
would deduce here

01:01:47.290 --> 01:01:49.690
that there is this
potential energy,

01:01:49.690 --> 01:01:51.720
and the amount of
work that I have

01:01:51.720 --> 01:01:53.820
to do to roll this off
the hill is the difference

01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:57.330
between the potential energy
between the two points.

01:01:57.330 --> 01:02:02.260
So here, similarly, I would
say that this delta W--

01:02:02.260 --> 01:02:07.890
I define it to be the difference
between some function that

01:02:07.890 --> 01:02:11.430
is called the internal
energy-- that depends

01:02:11.430 --> 01:02:13.440
on the final set of coordinates.

01:02:13.440 --> 01:02:15.980
And there's a whole
bunch of them.

01:02:15.980 --> 01:02:18.390
Think of them in some
pictorial context.

01:02:18.390 --> 01:02:21.560
Minus what you have initially.

01:02:26.320 --> 01:02:31.790
So in the same sense that
the zeroth law allowed

01:02:31.790 --> 01:02:36.940
me to construct some
function of coordinates that

01:02:36.940 --> 01:02:39.910
was relevant to
thermal equilibrium,

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:43.910
the first law allows me
to define another function

01:02:43.910 --> 01:02:46.165
of coordinates, which
is this internal energy.

01:02:51.560 --> 01:02:56.870
Of course, the internal energy
is the remnant of the energy

01:02:56.870 --> 01:02:59.030
that we know in
mechanical systems

01:02:59.030 --> 01:03:00.830
to be conserved quantity.

01:03:00.830 --> 01:03:02.750
And this is the
statement of fact.

01:03:02.750 --> 01:03:07.110
So far, nothing surprising.

01:03:07.110 --> 01:03:10.920
Now the real content
of the first law

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:13.620
is when we violate
this condition.

01:03:13.620 --> 01:03:20.290
So essentially, what we do is
we replace the adiabatic walls

01:03:20.290 --> 01:03:30.850
that were surrounding our
very same system with walls

01:03:30.850 --> 01:03:34.640
that allow the exchange of heat.

01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:38.690
And I do exactly the
same set of changes.

01:03:38.690 --> 01:03:41.410
So maybe in one
case I stretch this,

01:03:41.410 --> 01:03:43.310
and then I change the
volume, et cetera.

01:03:43.310 --> 01:03:46.500
I do exactly the
same set of changes

01:03:46.500 --> 01:03:50.160
that I did in this case,
I try to repeat them

01:03:50.160 --> 01:03:52.840
in the presence of
diathermic walls,

01:03:52.840 --> 01:03:57.430
go from the same initial
state to the same final state.

01:03:57.430 --> 01:03:59.020
So the initial
state is the same.

01:03:59.020 --> 01:04:02.220
The final state, I
postulate to be the same.

01:04:02.220 --> 01:04:05.990
And what is observed
is that, in this case,

01:04:05.990 --> 01:04:14.860
the diathermic walls--
which allow heat exchange--

01:04:14.860 --> 01:04:18.170
that the amount of work
that you have to do

01:04:18.170 --> 01:04:22.280
is not equal to the
change in internal energy.

01:04:25.684 --> 01:04:26.184
OK?

01:04:30.100 --> 01:04:37.460
Now you really believe that
energy is a good quantity.

01:04:37.460 --> 01:04:42.260
And so at this stage, you
make a postulate, if you like,

01:04:42.260 --> 01:04:45.690
it's the part of the corollary
of the first law that

01:04:45.690 --> 01:04:48.850
allows you to define
exactly what heat is.

01:04:48.850 --> 01:04:51.740
So you're gradually defining
all of the things that

01:04:51.740 --> 01:04:55.310
were missing in the
original formulation.

01:04:55.310 --> 01:05:03.340
You define this heat
input to the system

01:05:03.340 --> 01:05:13.270
to be the difference in
energy that you expected,

01:05:13.270 --> 01:05:15.570
minus the amount
of work that you

01:05:15.570 --> 01:05:19.920
did in the presence
of these walls.

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:21.820
OK?

01:05:21.820 --> 01:05:22.560
Yes?

01:05:22.560 --> 01:05:26.506
AUDIENCE: If we need the first
law to the point of heat--

01:05:26.506 --> 01:05:27.130
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:05:27.130 --> 01:05:31.542
AUDIENCE: --how did we define
[? adiabatic ?] used in--

01:05:31.542 --> 01:05:32.250
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:05:32.250 --> 01:05:35.270
AUDIENCE: --first law
and the zeroth law?

01:05:35.270 --> 01:05:37.860
PROFESSOR: As I said,
it's an idealization.

01:05:37.860 --> 01:05:40.270
So it's, in the same sense
that you can say well,

01:05:40.270 --> 01:05:43.600
how would you define
Newtonian mechanics

01:05:43.600 --> 01:05:47.310
that force is proportional to
mass times acceleration, what

01:05:47.310 --> 01:05:50.150
is the experimental
evidence for that?

01:05:50.150 --> 01:05:52.980
You can only do that really
when you go to vacuum.

01:05:52.980 --> 01:05:55.920
So what you can do
is you can gradually

01:05:55.920 --> 01:06:00.620
immerse your particle into
more and more dilute systems,

01:06:00.620 --> 01:06:03.910
and see what is the limiting
behavior in that sense.

01:06:03.910 --> 01:06:06.350
You can try to do
something similar here.

01:06:06.350 --> 01:06:08.610
You can imagine that
you put your system

01:06:08.610 --> 01:06:12.760
in some kind of a glass,
double glass, container,

01:06:12.760 --> 01:06:15.980
and you gradually pump
out all of the gas

01:06:15.980 --> 01:06:17.910
this is between the two of them.

01:06:17.910 --> 01:06:20.280
So that, ultimately,
you arrive at vacuum.

01:06:20.280 --> 01:06:22.080
You also have to
mirror things, so there

01:06:22.080 --> 01:06:24.760
is no radiation
exchange, et cetera.

01:06:24.760 --> 01:06:27.800
So gradually, you can try
to experimentally reach

01:06:27.800 --> 01:06:30.710
that idealization
and see what happens.

01:06:30.710 --> 01:06:33.220
But essentially, it
is certainly correct

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:36.630
that any statement that I
make about adiabatic walls

01:06:36.630 --> 01:06:37.900
is an isolation.

01:06:37.900 --> 01:06:40.202
But it's an isolation
in the same sense

01:06:40.202 --> 01:06:41.660
that when you think
about the point

01:06:41.660 --> 01:06:42.910
particle in Newton's laws.

01:06:48.881 --> 01:06:49.380
OK?

01:06:57.540 --> 01:06:59.830
Let's go a little bit
further with this.

01:07:09.490 --> 01:07:23.260
So we have that in
differential form,

01:07:23.260 --> 01:07:29.310
if I go from one point
in coordinate space

01:07:29.310 --> 01:07:31.870
that describes the
system in equilibrium,

01:07:31.870 --> 01:07:34.660
where energy's defined
to a nearby point,

01:07:34.660 --> 01:07:38.700
I can calculate what the value
of the change in this energy

01:07:38.700 --> 01:07:40.070
function is.

01:07:40.070 --> 01:07:44.230
And I can say that
there is a quantity, dE,

01:07:44.230 --> 01:07:46.730
that depends on a whole
bunch of coordinates that

01:07:46.730 --> 01:07:47.530
define the system.

01:07:50.140 --> 01:07:54.730
And what the first law
says is that if you

01:07:54.730 --> 01:07:57.840
try to operationally make
this change from one point

01:07:57.840 --> 01:08:02.250
to another point, you have to
supply work through the system,

01:08:02.250 --> 01:08:05.820
or you have to supply
heat through the system.

01:08:05.820 --> 01:08:10.760
And we write them in this form.

01:08:10.760 --> 01:08:13.435
And what this D
and d bar-- and we

01:08:13.435 --> 01:08:19.000
will encounter this many times
in future also and define

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:22.020
them better-- is that E
is a function of state.

01:08:22.020 --> 01:08:25.380
It depends on where you are
in this parameter space.

01:08:25.380 --> 01:08:30.260
So in the same sense that maybe
you have a function of x and y,

01:08:30.260 --> 01:08:33.520
could be like x
squared plus 3x y,

01:08:33.520 --> 01:08:37.149
I can define what dE is
in terms of the x and y.

01:08:37.149 --> 01:08:40.890
So that's where I
have this quantity.

01:08:40.890 --> 01:08:45.979
But dW and dQ depend on
precisely how this system

01:08:45.979 --> 01:08:48.410
was made to go
from here to here.

01:08:48.410 --> 01:08:52.430
And you can sort of go between
how much contribution to dE

01:08:52.430 --> 01:08:55.569
comes from here or from
there, by certainly say,

01:08:55.569 --> 01:08:57.529
changing the
properties of the walls

01:08:57.529 --> 01:09:01.319
from being adiabatic to
being diathermal, et cetera.

01:09:01.319 --> 01:09:06.630
So these quantities really, as
opposed to this quantity that

01:09:06.630 --> 01:09:09.109
depends on stage,
these quantities

01:09:09.109 --> 01:09:12.084
depend on path, the
conditions by which you

01:09:12.084 --> 01:09:13.819
implement a particular change.

01:09:18.819 --> 01:09:23.870
Now there is a desire, and
it's very important for us

01:09:23.870 --> 01:09:27.569
to actually construct
what this function is.

01:09:27.569 --> 01:09:31.540
You want to, sort of, know
what the energy function

01:09:31.540 --> 01:09:33.600
for, let's say, a
mechanical system is.

01:09:33.600 --> 01:09:36.744
In a potential, you want
to know what the form of E

01:09:36.744 --> 01:09:39.439
is and then you can do
a lot of things with it.

01:09:39.439 --> 01:09:45.090
So how do we construct that
for our thermodynamics system?

01:09:45.090 --> 01:09:47.689
Again, we can
idealize things and go

01:09:47.689 --> 01:09:52.434
to processes that are
so-called, quasi-static.

01:09:59.690 --> 01:10:07.640
Which effectively means
slow, or slow enough,

01:10:07.640 --> 01:10:12.750
to maintain equilibrium.

01:10:15.850 --> 01:10:18.240
And the general
idea is, suppose I

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:23.110
wanted to calculate what the
potential energy of a spring

01:10:23.110 --> 01:10:28.960
is, or what the potential energy
of a particle rolling on a hill

01:10:28.960 --> 01:10:34.290
is, well, one way that I could
do that is I could, let's say,

01:10:34.290 --> 01:10:39.180
pull on this sufficiently
slowly, so that as I'm pulling

01:10:39.180 --> 01:10:43.630
this by a certain amount,
the spring does not

01:10:43.630 --> 01:10:45.570
start to vibrate.

01:10:45.570 --> 01:10:48.890
And so the force that
I'm exerting externally,

01:10:48.890 --> 01:10:53.430
is really the force that
is internal to the spring.

01:10:53.430 --> 01:10:56.360
If I really push it
to rapidly, the spring

01:10:56.360 --> 01:10:58.090
will start to oscillate.

01:10:58.090 --> 01:11:01.370
There's really no relation
now between the external force

01:11:01.370 --> 01:11:04.300
that, let's say, is in uniform
value and the internal force

01:11:04.300 --> 01:11:05.810
that is oscillating.

01:11:05.810 --> 01:11:08.190
I don't want to do that
because when that happens

01:11:08.190 --> 01:11:11.760
I don't know where I am
in this coordinate space.

01:11:11.760 --> 01:11:13.970
I want to do things
sufficiently slowly

01:11:13.970 --> 01:11:17.500
so that I go from here
to here here-- every time

01:11:17.500 --> 01:11:23.220
I am on this plane that defines
my properties in equilibrium.

01:11:23.220 --> 01:11:26.630
If I do that, then I can
calculate the amount of work,

01:11:26.630 --> 01:11:32.850
and for the case
of the spring, it

01:11:32.850 --> 01:11:35.450
would be the force
times extension.

01:11:35.450 --> 01:11:37.370
And so we generalize
that, and we

01:11:37.370 --> 01:11:42.620
say that if I have multiple ways
of doing work on the system,

01:11:42.620 --> 01:11:45.560
there is the analog of
the change in length

01:11:45.560 --> 01:11:49.820
of the spring-- that is the
displacement of the spring,

01:11:49.820 --> 01:12:03.790
if you like-- multiplied by
some generalized force that

01:12:03.790 --> 01:12:05.179
is conjugate to that.

01:12:11.050 --> 01:12:15.850
And indeed,
mechanically, you would

01:12:15.850 --> 01:12:21.300
define the conjugate
variables by differentiation.

01:12:21.300 --> 01:12:23.830
So if you, for example,
know the potential energy

01:12:23.830 --> 01:12:26.250
of the spring as a
function of its length,

01:12:26.250 --> 01:12:29.420
you take a derivative and
you know what the force is.

01:12:29.420 --> 01:12:32.570
So this is essentially
writing that relationship

01:12:32.570 --> 01:12:35.230
for the case of the
spring, generalize

01:12:35.230 --> 01:12:37.280
to multiple coordinates.

01:12:37.280 --> 01:12:43.330
And we can make a table of
what these displacements are

01:12:43.330 --> 01:12:47.450
and the corresponding
coordinates for the types

01:12:47.450 --> 01:12:49.580
of systems that we are
likely to encounter.

01:13:01.150 --> 01:13:03.250
So what is x?

01:13:03.250 --> 01:13:05.220
What is j?

01:13:05.220 --> 01:13:08.010
And the first thing
that we mentioned

01:13:08.010 --> 01:13:10.620
was the case of the wire.

01:13:10.620 --> 01:13:14.860
And for the wire we can-- the
displacement of the length

01:13:14.860 --> 01:13:16.860
is important, and the
conjugate variable

01:13:16.860 --> 01:13:20.450
is the force with which
you are pulling on this.

01:13:20.450 --> 01:13:25.380
In the first problem set, you
will deal-- in the first test

01:13:25.380 --> 01:13:29.880
preparation, you will deal
with the case of film.

01:13:29.880 --> 01:13:33.856
And for the film, what you
do is you change the area,

01:13:33.856 --> 01:13:35.230
or if you have a
balloon, you can

01:13:35.230 --> 01:13:37.870
blow on the balloon, and the
surface area of the balloon

01:13:37.870 --> 01:13:38.860
changes.

01:13:38.860 --> 01:13:41.730
And there's a corresponding
conjugate variable

01:13:41.730 --> 01:13:44.405
to that which is called
the surface tension.

01:13:48.880 --> 01:13:52.150
This is essentially the same
thing, going from one dimension

01:13:52.150 --> 01:13:53.900
to two dimension.

01:13:53.900 --> 01:13:56.690
And if I were to go
one dimension higher,

01:13:56.690 --> 01:14:02.410
in the case of the gas, I
have the volume of the box.

01:14:02.410 --> 01:14:06.330
And I went through this
just for the notation

01:14:06.330 --> 01:14:09.620
that the hydrostatic
pressure of the work

01:14:09.620 --> 01:14:13.840
is defined to be
minus p w-- minus PBV.

01:14:13.840 --> 01:14:14.480
Sorry.

01:14:14.480 --> 01:14:20.050
pW is minus PVV, as opposed to,
say, the force of the spring,

01:14:20.050 --> 01:14:21.570
that is FDL.

01:14:21.570 --> 01:14:23.600
It's just, again,
matter of definition

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:27.050
and how we define the
sign of the pressure.

01:14:27.050 --> 01:14:31.720
And for the case of the magnet
that we also briefly mentioned,

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:34.850
we have here MDB.

01:14:34.850 --> 01:14:39.720
The one thing that you
can see is the trend

01:14:39.720 --> 01:14:43.020
that all of these
quantities, if you

01:14:43.020 --> 01:14:46.920
make the size of your system
twice as big, these quantities

01:14:46.920 --> 01:14:49.240
will get proportionately bigger.

01:14:49.240 --> 01:14:50.420
So they're called extensive.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:58.830
Whereas the force and all the
other quantities are intensive.

01:15:04.070 --> 01:15:08.540
So what we've established
is that if we focus only

01:15:08.540 --> 01:15:11.990
on these types of
transformations, that

01:15:11.990 --> 01:15:18.430
don't include heat, we can
relate the change in energy

01:15:18.430 --> 01:15:20.500
directly to dW.

01:15:20.500 --> 01:15:24.590
And the dW, we can write
as the sum over i Ji dxi.

01:15:28.290 --> 01:15:33.520
Now in order to really
get dE, in general,

01:15:33.520 --> 01:15:35.280
I have to add to this dQ.

01:15:38.320 --> 01:15:45.366
And so really the
question that we have is,

01:15:45.366 --> 01:15:50.480
is there some kind
of analog of dW

01:15:50.480 --> 01:15:54.130
that we can write down for dQ?

01:15:54.130 --> 01:15:58.250
And if you think about it,
if you have two springs that

01:15:58.250 --> 01:16:01.360
are in equilibrium, so
that the thing does not

01:16:01.360 --> 01:16:04.435
go one way or the other,
the force exerted from one

01:16:04.435 --> 01:16:07.190
is the same as the force
exerted on the other.

01:16:07.190 --> 01:16:10.490
So in equilibrium, mechanical
equilibrium forces,

01:16:10.490 --> 01:16:14.100
pressures, et cetera,
are generally the same.

01:16:14.100 --> 01:16:17.340
And we've established that when
you are in thermal equilibrium,

01:16:17.340 --> 01:16:19.550
temperatures are the same.

01:16:19.550 --> 01:16:23.840
So we have a very good
guess that we should really

01:16:23.840 --> 01:16:27.640
have temperature appearing here.

01:16:27.640 --> 01:16:31.020
And then the question that
we'll sort of build on

01:16:31.020 --> 01:16:33.720
is what is the analog
of the quantity

01:16:33.720 --> 01:16:34.998
that we have to put here.

01:16:44.090 --> 01:16:50.760
Let me finish by telling
you one other story that

01:16:50.760 --> 01:16:53.600
is related to the ideal gas.

01:16:53.600 --> 01:16:56.840
I said that for every
one of these laws,

01:16:56.840 --> 01:17:02.460
we can kind of come up with
a peculiar feature that

01:17:02.460 --> 01:17:05.330
is unique to the case
of the ideal gas.

01:17:05.330 --> 01:17:08.460
And there is a property
related to its energy

01:17:08.460 --> 01:17:11.610
that we will shortly explore.

01:17:11.610 --> 01:17:16.970
But let me first say what the
consequence of these kinds

01:17:16.970 --> 01:17:20.450
of relations for
measurable quantities

01:17:20.450 --> 01:17:24.650
that we can already
try to deduce are.

01:17:24.650 --> 01:17:30.800
So one thing that you
can relate to heat,

01:17:30.800 --> 01:17:35.855
and properties of particular
material, is the heat capacity.

01:17:38.560 --> 01:17:43.720
So what you can do is you
can take your material

01:17:43.720 --> 01:17:48.670
and put some amount
of heat into it.

01:17:48.670 --> 01:17:52.050
And ask, what is the
corresponding change

01:17:52.050 --> 01:17:54.087
in temperature?

01:17:54.087 --> 01:17:55.420
That would be the heat capacity.

01:17:58.050 --> 01:18:02.050
Now this bar that
we have over here,

01:18:02.050 --> 01:18:09.420
tells me that this quantity--
which we will denote on C--

01:18:09.420 --> 01:18:16.460
will depend on the path
through which the heat is

01:18:16.460 --> 01:18:17.910
added to the system.

01:18:17.910 --> 01:18:22.760
Because we've established that,
depending on how you add heat

01:18:22.760 --> 01:18:25.140
to the system, the
change that you

01:18:25.140 --> 01:18:28.410
have in the coordinate
space is going

01:18:28.410 --> 01:18:30.220
to be distinct potentially.

01:18:30.220 --> 01:18:32.220
Actually, we establish
the other way

01:18:32.220 --> 01:18:35.300
that for a given change
in the coordinate system,

01:18:35.300 --> 01:18:37.340
the amount of the
Q depends on path,

01:18:37.340 --> 01:18:40.370
so they're kind of
equivalent statements.

01:18:40.370 --> 01:18:49.880
So if I'm dealing with a gas,
I can add the heat to it,

01:18:49.880 --> 01:18:52.780
at least among many
other possibilities,

01:18:52.780 --> 01:18:54.590
in two distinct ways.

01:18:54.590 --> 01:19:01.190
I can do this at constant
volume or at constant pressure.

01:19:01.190 --> 01:19:05.030
So if I think about
the coordinate space

01:19:05.030 --> 01:19:08.800
of the gas, which
is PV, and I start

01:19:08.800 --> 01:19:11.720
from some particular
point, I can either

01:19:11.720 --> 01:19:14.420
go along a path like
this, or I can go along

01:19:14.420 --> 01:19:17.630
the path like this, depending
on which one of these quantities

01:19:17.630 --> 01:19:20.310
I keep fixed.

01:19:20.310 --> 01:19:25.060
So then in one
case what I need is

01:19:25.060 --> 01:19:29.650
the change in Q
at constant v, dT.

01:19:29.650 --> 01:19:33.078
In the other case, this
change in Q, a constant P, dT.

01:19:36.360 --> 01:19:39.220
Now a consequence
of the first law

01:19:39.220 --> 01:19:48.735
is that I know that dQ's
are related to dE minus dW.

01:19:48.735 --> 01:19:52.870
And dW for the gas is minus PdV.

01:19:52.870 --> 01:19:56.030
So I can write it
in this fashion.

01:19:56.030 --> 01:20:00.760
Divided by dT, and in one
case, done at constant V,

01:20:00.760 --> 01:20:05.680
and in the other case,
done at constant p.

01:20:10.110 --> 01:20:12.620
The distinction
between these two paths

01:20:12.620 --> 01:20:18.090
immediately becomes clear,
because along the paths where

01:20:18.090 --> 01:20:21.500
the volume is kept
constant, there

01:20:21.500 --> 01:20:29.430
is no mechanical work that is
done along the this path, yes?

01:20:29.430 --> 01:20:32.470
And so this contribution is 0.

01:20:32.470 --> 01:20:35.360
And you have the
result that this

01:20:35.360 --> 01:20:39.960
is going to be related
to the change in energy

01:20:39.960 --> 01:20:43.270
with temperature at
constant V, whereas here you

01:20:43.270 --> 01:20:48.010
have the change in energy,
in temperature at constant P,

01:20:48.010 --> 01:20:53.426
plus P dV by dT at constant P.

01:20:53.426 --> 01:20:58.220
So there is some additional
manipulations of derivatives

01:20:58.220 --> 01:21:04.420
that is involved, but
rather than looking

01:21:04.420 --> 01:21:13.460
at that in the general case,
I will follow the consequence

01:21:13.460 --> 01:21:17.410
of that for a particular
example, which

01:21:17.410 --> 01:21:20.130
is ideal gas expansion.

01:21:27.070 --> 01:21:31.020
So as this is an observation
called Joule's experiment.

01:21:31.020 --> 01:21:36.140
I take a gas that is
adiabatically isolated

01:21:36.140 --> 01:21:38.010
from its environment.

01:21:38.010 --> 01:21:43.880
I connect it, also maintaining
adiabatic isolation

01:21:43.880 --> 01:21:45.880
to another chamber.

01:21:45.880 --> 01:21:49.070
And initially all
of the gas is here,

01:21:49.070 --> 01:21:51.920
and this chamber is empty.

01:21:51.920 --> 01:21:59.247
And then I remove this, and
the gas goes and occupies

01:21:59.247 --> 01:21:59.830
both chambers.

01:22:03.170 --> 01:22:06.570
Observation, there
is some temperature

01:22:06.570 --> 01:22:11.090
initially in this system
that I can measure.

01:22:11.090 --> 01:22:15.240
Finally, I can measure the
temperature of this system.

01:22:15.240 --> 01:22:17.522
And I find that the two
temperatures are the same.

01:22:24.610 --> 01:22:27.180
In this example,
since the whole thing

01:22:27.180 --> 01:22:32.080
was adiabatically
isolated, that the Q is 0.

01:22:32.080 --> 01:22:36.130
There is no mechanical work
that done on the system,

01:22:36.130 --> 01:22:41.260
so delta W is also 0.

01:22:41.260 --> 01:22:45.880
And since delta is
the same, I conclude

01:22:45.880 --> 01:22:53.880
that delta E is the
same for this two cases.

01:22:53.880 --> 01:22:56.840
Now, in principle,
E is a function

01:22:56.840 --> 01:23:00.500
of pressure and volume.

01:23:00.500 --> 01:23:04.590
And pressure and volume
certainly changed very much

01:23:04.590 --> 01:23:09.010
by going from that
place to another place.

01:23:09.010 --> 01:23:10.290
OK, so let's follow that.

01:23:10.290 --> 01:23:15.630
So E we said is a function
of pressure and volume.

01:23:15.630 --> 01:23:18.760
Now since I know that
for the ideal gas,

01:23:18.760 --> 01:23:21.530
the product of pressure
and volume is temperature,

01:23:21.530 --> 01:23:25.040
I can certainly exchange
one of these variables

01:23:25.040 --> 01:23:26.240
for temperature.

01:23:26.240 --> 01:23:28.000
So I can write,
let's say, pressure

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:31.790
to be proportional to
temperature over volume.

01:23:31.790 --> 01:23:34.720
And then rewrite
this as a function

01:23:34.720 --> 01:23:36.280
of temperature and volume.

01:23:39.400 --> 01:23:45.410
Now I know that in this
process the volume changed,

01:23:45.410 --> 01:23:48.500
but the temperature
did not change.

01:23:48.500 --> 01:23:52.390
And therefore, the internal
energy that did not change

01:23:52.390 --> 01:23:55.540
can only be a function
of temperature.

01:23:55.540 --> 01:23:58.840
So this Joule expansion
experiment immediately

01:23:58.840 --> 01:24:02.390
tells me that while internal
energy, in principle,

01:24:02.390 --> 01:24:05.570
is a function of P
and V, it is really

01:24:05.570 --> 01:24:07.590
a function of the
product of P and V,

01:24:07.590 --> 01:24:09.050
because the product
of P and V, we

01:24:09.050 --> 01:24:12.380
established to be
proportional to temperature.

01:24:12.380 --> 01:24:13.420
OK?

01:24:13.420 --> 01:24:17.340
So now if I go and look
at these expressions,

01:24:17.340 --> 01:24:21.830
I can see that these, dE by
dT, and irrespective of V and P

01:24:21.830 --> 01:24:25.660
is the same thing, because E
only depends on temperature.

01:24:25.660 --> 01:24:31.075
And since V is-- we know that PV
is proportional to temperature,

01:24:31.075 --> 01:24:37.950
a constant P, dV by dT
is the same as V over T.

01:24:37.950 --> 01:24:41.550
And so if I look at the
difference between those two

01:24:41.550 --> 01:24:46.470
expressions, what I find
is that this part cancels.

01:24:46.470 --> 01:24:52.520
This part gives me the value
of this product, PV over T,

01:24:52.520 --> 01:24:55.900
which we said is a constant.

01:24:55.900 --> 01:25:00.450
And it is certainly depends
on the amount of gas

01:25:00.450 --> 01:25:02.630
that you have.

01:25:02.630 --> 01:25:05.880
And so you can pick a
particular amount of gas.

01:25:05.880 --> 01:25:08.175
You can experimentally
verify this phenomenon,

01:25:08.175 --> 01:25:11.710
that the difference of heat
capacity along these two paths

01:25:11.710 --> 01:25:13.160
is a constant.

01:25:13.160 --> 01:25:17.880
That constant is the same
for the same amount of gas

01:25:17.880 --> 01:25:21.210
for different types of
argon, krypton, et cetera.

01:25:21.210 --> 01:25:24.030
And since it is
proportional, eventually

01:25:24.030 --> 01:25:28.000
to the amount of matter,
we will ultimately

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:32.520
see that it can be set to
be the number of particles

01:25:32.520 --> 01:25:36.770
making up the gas in some
constant of proportionality

01:25:36.770 --> 01:25:41.070
that we will identify later
in statistical physics

01:25:41.070 --> 01:25:42.920
is the Boltzmann
parameter, which

01:25:42.920 --> 01:25:49.257
is 1.43 times 10 to the
minus 23 or whatever it is.

01:25:53.240 --> 01:25:56.065
All of this depends
partly on the definition

01:25:56.065 --> 01:25:58.890
that you made of temperature.

01:25:58.890 --> 01:26:03.630
What we will do next
time is to review

01:26:03.630 --> 01:26:06.310
all of this, because I've went
through them a little bit more

01:26:06.310 --> 01:26:14.390
rapidly, and try to identify
what the conjugate variable is

01:26:14.390 --> 01:26:17.790
that we have to put
for temperature,

01:26:17.790 --> 01:26:22.380
so that we can write the form of
dE in a more symmetric fashion.

01:26:22.380 --> 01:26:23.889
Thank you.

